   ‘priest’. Compare   Cory  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Corr","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, Aidan, Brendan.","Irish:","Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Corra</b> ‘descendant of <i>Corra</i>’, a personal name from <i>corr</i> ‘spear, pointed object’. It is occasionally translated into English as   Weir   (from Irish <i>cora</i> ‘weir’)."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas Corry was born in 1425, in Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland, his father, Sir William Corrie, was 25 and his mother, Lady Lydia Corrie, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Eufemia de Herries Lindsay. He died in 1504, in his hometown, at the age of 79."},"et":{"1425–1504":"1425–1504","1450–1478":"1450–1478","1470–1536":"1470–1536","1400–1460":"1400–1460","1536":"1536","1425":"1425","1478":"1478","1400":"1400","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1470":"1470","1504":"1504","Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland","Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1425–1504":"1425–1504","1450–1478":"1450–1478","1470–1536":"1470–1536","1400–1460":"1400–1460","1536":"1536","1425":"1425","1478":"1478","1400":"1400","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1470":"1470","1504":"1504","Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland","Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1425–1504":"1425–1504","1450–1478":"1450–1478","1470–1536":"1470–1536","1400–1460":"1400–1460","1536":"1536","1425":"1425","1478":"1478","1400":"1400","1450":"1450